/*js numbers are always stored as double precision floating point numbers , following the international IEEE 754 standard
this format stores numbers in 64 bits, where the number (the fraction) is stored in bits 0 to 51, the exponent in bits 52 to 62, and the sign bit is 63
integers without a period or exponent are accurate up to 15 digits. . for example 9999999999999999[15 digit] is same but 9999999999999999[16 digit ] is 100000000000000000
.Floating point arithmetic is not always 100% accurate.
1. if we add 2 numbers then the result also be number
2. if we add 2 strings , the number will be a string concatenation
3.add 2 numbers and the strings the the number will be string
4. add 2 strings and number the the result will be string .
 */
 // ADD TWO STRINGS RESULT WILL BE STRING 
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<body>

<h2>JavaScript Numbers</h2>

<p>If you add two numeric strings, the result will be a concatenated string:</p>

<p id="demo"></p>

<script>
 let x ="20";
 let y ="60";
 let z = x + y;
 document.getElementById("demo").innerHTML=z;
 </script>
 </body>
 </html>

 // OUTPUT is 2060

 <!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<body>

<h2>JavaScript Numbers</h2>

<p>If you add two numeric strings, the result will be a concatenated string:</p>

<p id="demo"></p>

<script>
let x = "10";
let y = 20;
let z = x + y;
 document.getElementById("demo").innerHTML=z;
 </script>
 </body>
 </html>

 //OUTPUT 1020

// THE MOST COMMON MISTAKE
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<body>

<h2>JavaScript Numbers</h2>

<p>If you add two numeric strings, the result will be a concatenated string:</p>

<p id="demo"></p>

<script>
let x = 10;
let y = 20;
document.getElementBtId("demo").innerHTML="The result is:" +x +y;
</script>
</body>
</html>
// The most common mistake is 30 but the real output is : 1020

// two numbers add and the string add in it then the result will be number and string
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<body>

<h2>JavaScript Numbers</h2>

<p>A common mistake is to expect this result to be 102030:</p>

<p id="demo"></p>

<script>
let x = 10;
let y = 20;
let z = "30";
let result = x + y + z;
document.getElementById("demo").innerHTML = result;
</script>

</body>
</html>
// output is 3030


// js will try to convert strings to numbers when dividing
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<body>

<h2>JavaScript Numbers</h2>

<p>JavaScript will try to convert strings to numbers when dividing:</p>

<p id="demo"></p>

<script>
let x = "1000";
let y ="100"
let z = x/y;
document.getElementById("demo").innerHTML= z;
</script>
</body>
</html>
// Output  10


// Not A Number NaN 
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<body>

<h2>JavaScript Numbers</h2>

<p>A number divided by a non-numeric string becomes NaN (Not a Number):</p>

<p id="demo"></p>

<script>
document.getElementById("demo").innerHTML = 100 / "Apple";
</script>

</body>
</html> // output NaN

// 10/"100" = NaN

 
